commentary: Paul to Jadeja, OUT fuller on the stumps, jams his bat down in time to send it to midwicket. Quick single taken, safe despite the fielder running in and effecting a direct hit at the striker's end. wait a minute, replays show Jadeja was out of the crease! The umpire didn't go upstairs though. And now they're going up to the third umpire. Which means Jadeja will be ruled out. Bit bizarre sequence of events. Wrong process, but right decision? If a West Indies fielder appealed when the direct hit was effected, there is still a justification for going up to the third umpire, even if late in the proceedings. But is it okay to go up after having seen the replay? That's one for the law mandarins to figure out.

commentary: Chahar to Ambris, OUT big appeal for lbw, and it's given. Ambris doesn't review. Length ball angling into the stumps, and Ambris looks to flick. He was playing for outswing, I think - a dangerous thing to do if you're playing across the line like that - and the ball keeps going with the angle instead and brushes front pad before hitting his back pad. Hitting middle and leg, according to ball-tracking. No front-foot stride at all from Ambris

commentary: Kuldeep Yadav to Hope, no run big appeal for lbw, but is that turning too much? Not given by umpire Shaun George, and India have reviewed. Classic left-arm wristspinner's delivery. Floating across the right-hander, dipping on him, pitching outside off, and ripping back in to beat the inside edge of the forward defensive. Impact is in line with off stump, but, as I suspected, it's turning too much and missing leg stump, according to ball-tracking. Pretty big stride too

commentary: Chahar to Hope, SIX runs bang. Back of a length, angling into the stumps, and it's the knuckle ball. Hope slides away to the leg side to make himself room, holds his shape beautifully, and flat-bats it hard, back over the bowler's head, and over the boundary as well. Super shot

commentary: Chahar to Hope, FOUR runs and there's the hundred. It's been a struggle, but he's hung in there, fought the conditions and his own lack of fluency, and he's now earning the rewards. Short from Chahar, and he pulls it away to the right of midwicket
